          "body": "Chapters 13-24 of Numbers 31 form the chapter's liturgical core. Even warriors who have fought at YHWH's direct command incur ritual defilement from contact with the dead (31:19) — a fact that surprises readers who expect divine sanction to confer automatic purity. It does not. Numbers operates with a category of holiness that is objective and transferable, not merely moral and motivational. The soldiers who obeyed God's command must still remain outside the camp for seven days, undergo double purification on days three and seven, and wash their clothes before re-entry (31:19-24). Material plunder is similarly contaminated: metal objects that can withstand fire must pass through fire and then the water of purification (Num. 19); organic materials pass only through water (31:22-23). Eleazar the priest — not Moses — promulgates these metal-purification regulations (31:21), signaling a transfer of authority in the post-battle phase from military to priestly leadership. Douglas Moo (commenting on analogous New Covenant holiness themes) and John Owen (in his treatment of indwelling sin) both observed that defilement operates at a level beneath conscious choice — contact with death and foreign contamination creates objective need for cleansing regardless of the agent's intentions. Numbers 31 embeds that principle in practice."
